<Layout title="Surgical Treatments">
	<section class="page-header">
		<div class="container">
			<h1>Surgical Fertility Treatments</h1>
			<p>Procedures to diagnose and correct structural issues affecting fertility.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<h2>Overview</h2>
		<p>Surgical treatments address physical abnormalities that may prevent conception or successful pregnancy. These procedures can be diagnostic (to identify problems) or therapeutic (to fix them), and often both.</p>

		<h2>Laparoscopy</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>What It Is</h3>
			<p>Minimally invasive surgery using a thin camera (laparoscope) inserted through small incisions in the abdomen to view and treat pelvic organs.</p>

			<h3>Used For</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Endometriosis:</strong> Removal of endometrial implants and scar tissue</li>
				<li><strong>Ovarian cysts:</strong> Removal while preserving ovarian tissue</li>
				<li><strong>Fallopian tubes:</strong> Assess patency, remove hydrosalpinx</li>
				<li><strong>Fibroids:</strong> Removal of subserosal or intramural fibroids</li>
				<li><strong>Ectopic pregnancy:</strong> Treatment of tubal pregnancy</li>
				<li><strong>Unexplained infertility:</strong> Diagnostic exploration</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Procedure Details</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>General anesthesia</li>
				<li>2-4 small incisions (5-12mm)</li>
				<li>Outpatient; go home same day</li>
				<li>Recovery: 1-2 weeks</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Costs</h3>
			<table>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Diagnostic laparoscopy</td>
						<td>$5,000-$10,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Operative laparoscopy (treatment)</td>
						<td>$10,000-$25,000</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>
			<p><em>Insurance often covers diagnostic and medically necessary procedures.</em></p>
		</div>

		<h2>Hysteroscopy</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>What It Is</h3>
			<p>A thin camera inserted through the cervix into the uterus to view and treat problems inside the uterine cavity.</p>

			<h3>Used For</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Uterine polyps:</strong> Removal of endometrial polyps</li>
				<li><strong>Submucosal fibroids:</strong> Fibroids protruding into uterine cavity</li>
				<li><strong>Uterine septum:</strong> Division and removal of the septum</li>
				<li><strong>Asherman's syndrome:</strong> Removal of intrauterine adhesions/scar tissue</li>
				<li><strong>Retained tissue:</strong> After miscarriage or D&C</li>
				<li><strong>Abnormal bleeding:</strong> Diagnosis and treatment</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Procedure Details</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Local, sedation, or general anesthesia</li>
				<li>No incisions (through cervix)</li>
				<li>Outpatient procedure</li>
				<li>Recovery: 1-2 days</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Costs</h3>
			<table>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Diagnostic hysteroscopy</td>
						<td>$1,500-$5,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Operative hysteroscopy</td>
						<td>$5,000-$15,000</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>
		</div>

		<h2>Myomectomy</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>What It Is</h3>
			<p>Surgical removal of uterine fibroids while preserving the uterus.</p>

			<h3>Types</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Hysteroscopic:</strong> For fibroids inside the cavity (least invasive)</li>
				<li><strong>Laparoscopic:</strong> For fibroids on the outside or in the wall</li>
				<li><strong>Robotic-assisted:</strong> Laparoscopic with robotic precision</li>
				<li><strong>Abdominal (open):</strong> For large or numerous fibroids</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>When It Helps Fertility</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Submucosal fibroids (inside cavity) - clear benefit</li>
				<li>Large intramural fibroids (in wall) - may help</li>
				<li>Subserosal fibroids (on outside) - unlikely to affect fertility</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Recovery</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Hysteroscopic: 1-2 days</li>
				<li>Laparoscopic: 1-2 weeks</li>
				<li>Abdominal: 4-6 weeks</li>
				<li>Wait 3-6 months before attempting pregnancy</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Costs</h3>
			<table>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Hysteroscopic myomectomy</td>
						<td>$5,000-$12,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Laparoscopic myomectomy</td>
						<td>$10,000-$25,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Abdominal myomectomy</td>
						<td>$15,000-$30,000</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>
		</div>

		<h2>Tubal Surgery</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>Tubal Ligation Reversal</h3>
			<p>Reconnecting fallopian tubes after sterilization.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Success depends on type of original ligation and remaining tube length</li>
				<li>40-80% pregnancy rates if tubes can be reconnected</li>
				<li>Alternative: IVF (bypasses tubes entirely)</li>
				<li>Cost: $6,000-$15,000 (rarely covered by insurance)</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Salpingostomy/Fimbrioplasty</h3>
			<p>Opening blocked fallopian tubes or repairing the fimbriae (finger-like projections).</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Limited success rates (20-30%)</li>
				<li>Increased ectopic pregnancy risk</li>
				<li>IVF often preferred over tubal repair</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Salpingectomy</h3>
			<p>Removal of damaged fallopian tubes, often recommended before IVF.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Hydrosalpinx (fluid-filled tube) can reduce IVF success</li>
				<li>Removing damaged tubes improves IVF outcomes by 50%</li>
				<li>Required for ectopic pregnancy treatment in some cases</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<h2>Male Fertility Surgery</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>Varicocele Repair</h3>
			<p>Correction of enlarged veins in the scrotum.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Varicoceles found in 40% of infertile men</li>
				<li>May improve sperm count and motility</li>
				<li>Options: Microsurgical, laparoscopic, or embolization</li>
				<li>Cost: $5,000-$15,000</li>
				<li>Results seen 3-6 months after surgery</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Vasectomy Reversal</h3>
			<p>Reconnecting the vas deferens after vasectomy.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Success depends on time since vasectomy</li>
				<li>&lt;10 years: 75-95% sperm return</li>
				<li>&gt;15 years: 30-70% sperm return</li>
				<li>Pregnancy rates: 30-75%</li>
				<li>Cost: $5,000-$15,000</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Sperm Retrieval Procedures</h3>
			<p>For men with azoospermia (no sperm in ejaculate):</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>TESA:</strong> Testicular sperm aspiration (needle biopsy)</li>
				<li><strong>TESE:</strong> Testicular sperm extraction (surgical biopsy)</li>
				<li><strong>Micro-TESE:</strong> Microscope-assisted extraction</li>
				<li><strong>MESA:</strong> Microsurgical epididymal sperm aspiration</li>
				<li>Cost: $3,000-$15,000</li>
				<li>Sperm used with ICSI during IVF</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<h2>When Surgery vs. IVF?</h2>
		<table>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Consider Surgery When</th>
					<th>Consider IVF When</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>Young age (&lt;35)</td>
					<td>Advanced age (&gt;38)</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Single correctable issue</td>
					<td>Multiple fertility factors</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Good ovarian reserve</td>
					<td>Diminished ovarian reserve</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Want multiple children over time</td>
					<td>Limited time to conceive</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Prefer to try natural conception</td>
					<td>Need genetic testing</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Surgery likely to fully resolve issue</td>
					<td>Severe damage unlikely to be repaired</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

		<div class="info-box">
			<strong>Combined Approach:</strong> Sometimes surgery is recommended before IVF - for example, removing a hydrosalpinx or large fibroids to improve IVF success rates.
		</div>

		<h2>Finding a Surgeon</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Look for fellowship-trained reproductive endocrinologists or reproductive surgeons</li>
			<li>Ask about their experience with your specific condition</li>
			<li>Inquire about minimally invasive techniques</li>
			<li>Understand the expected impact on your fertility</li>
		</ul>

